pomegranate.title: I would like the Date sort for items in DPUL have the options of Ascending and Descending

comments.body:
This will require a data migration because the exhibits all save their configurations individually, so making the change in the catalog controller doesn't actually populate through all the exhibits.

Here's my plan.

1. Add new sort options `sort_date_desc` and `sort_date_asc`. Remove current `sort_date` option.
1. Run a rake task that iterates through every exhibit removing `sort_date` and adding in the new options.

This means exhibits won't have any date sort options in the short amount of time between deployment and completion of the rake task. @kelea99 is that acceptable? if not let me know and it's very easy to do it in 2 steps instead.

pulfa.title: Request edit of strict schema to display all local, controlled attribute values

comments.body:
I’m afraid I have bad news on this:

“For content completion, Oxygen XML Editor uses just one schema”
https://www.oxygenxml.com/doc/versions/21.1/ug-editor/topics/associate-schema-to-document.html

In other words, for the functionality you are requesting (the drop-down menu), we need to choose between the EAD schema and the local schema. The only workaround would be to go to a fully local schema that incorporates our local validation rules. That would be very hard to maintain though, so I don’t recommend it.

It’s possible to associate multiple schemas with a document type, if that would be helpful. This would at least make error messages from both schemas show up at the same time. Let me know if you want me to walk you through the setup.

Regine Heberlein
Library IT Data Analyst
609-258-6156
heberlei@princeton.edu

unitid @ type “itemnumber” or “accessionnumber”. These values show up when a user validates a file if there is an error; but they don't display in a pop-up window for users to select at the time of encoding as attribute values do via the EAD schema, for instance, unitdate @ type "inclusive" and "bulk."
